WEBVTT

00:02.830 --> 00:04.420
Jackson: Freezing.

00:04.420 --> 00:05.420
Choking.

00:05.420 --> 00:06.880
Getting tongue-tied.

00:06.880 --> 00:09.120
It's what we call it
when your mind

00:09.120 --> 00:11.000
goes from brilliant
to blank.

00:11.000 --> 00:15.170
We should only be gone
a day, two max.

00:15.170 --> 00:17.170
If you need me before that,
you can just --

00:17.170 --> 00:20.040
Please, Harriet's dying
for some quality time

00:20.040 --> 00:21.380
with her grandmama.

00:21.380 --> 00:24.960
Could've just
taken her with me. [ Sighs ]

00:24.960 --> 00:28.330
You can prepare
all you want.

00:28.330 --> 00:30.120
Aren't you gonna say, like,
"Go, child?

00:30.120 --> 00:31.580
You're being ridiculous."

00:31.580 --> 00:34.500
But the feeling can still
hit you, out of nowhere.

00:34.500 --> 00:36.920
If you're having
second thoughts,

00:36.920 --> 00:39.080
we could bring
your patient here.

00:39.080 --> 00:41.580
No, I told you,
we've got a girl

00:41.580 --> 00:43.830
who needs
a throat transplant

00:43.830 --> 00:46.580
and a donor
in the same exact hospital.

00:46.580 --> 00:48.120
We can't risk moving
either of them.

00:48.120 --> 00:51.460
[ Sighs ] I know.
I just meant...

00:51.460 --> 00:53.710
So when it hits you,
when your mind shuts down,

00:53.710 --> 00:56.000
when you open your mouth
and no words come out,

00:56.000 --> 00:57.250
the good news is...

00:57.250 --> 00:58.540
If you have something
to say, say it.

01:03.080 --> 01:04.330
Nothing.

01:06.330 --> 01:08.460
I'm sure you'll be
just fine.

01:08.460 --> 01:09.790
It happens to all of us.

01:32.620 --> 01:34.000
Wait.
Where is Grey?

01:34.000 --> 01:35.250
Since when is
April coming?

01:35.250 --> 01:38.960
Oh. Grey called to tell me
that Zola has flu.

01:38.960 --> 01:40.670
And you didn't think
to tell me that?

01:40.670 --> 01:42.830
I knew you'd need
a capable surgeon to assist,

01:42.830 --> 01:44.960
and April's
more than capable.

01:44.960 --> 01:46.790
Hello.
Hi, Catherine.

01:46.790 --> 01:48.420
Hi.
You have everything you need?

01:48.420 --> 01:51.210
Yes, of course.

01:51.210 --> 01:54.960
Okay. All right.

01:54.960 --> 01:56.380
You ready?

01:59.290 --> 02:00.330
I'll put her
in the car.

02:00.330 --> 02:01.710
Jackson, go.

02:01.710 --> 02:03.500
Miss Harriet and I
have plans.

02:03.500 --> 02:04.920
No medical journals,
all right?

02:04.920 --> 02:05.960
I don't need her
looking at

02:05.960 --> 02:07.250
flayed-open
surgical fields.

02:07.250 --> 02:08.920
Give me my child.

02:11.380 --> 02:12.830
Bye, baby.

02:12.830 --> 02:14.750
♪♪

02:23.540 --> 02:24.920
Bye, baby.

02:27.250 --> 02:28.620
Can I take your bag,
Dr. Grey?

02:28.620 --> 02:30.120
Uh, uh,
it's Dr. Kepner.

02:30.120 --> 02:31.290
I'm so sorry.
The manifest said --

02:31.290 --> 02:33.710
It's okay. Dr. Grey got hijacked
by my mother.

02:36.250 --> 02:38.460
[ Sighs ]

02:38.460 --> 02:41.040
This is amazing.

02:41.040 --> 02:42.670
Why have we never
taken your plane before?

02:42.670 --> 02:45.250
It's --
It's not my plane.

02:45.250 --> 02:47.080
It's your name
right out there.

02:47.080 --> 02:50.040
Right on the wing,
great big letters -- Avery.

02:50.040 --> 02:51.420
Yeah, but --
So it's your plane.

02:51.420 --> 02:53.620
No, it's the family plane.
It's not my plane.

02:53.620 --> 02:55.750
Well, yeah.

02:55.750 --> 02:58.540
It's Catherine's, too.
I mean...

02:58.540 --> 03:01.250
[ Sighs ]

03:01.250 --> 03:03.750
I mean, she did make
the Avery Foundation what it is.

03:03.750 --> 03:06.120
Seems right she should
get to fly anywhere
she wants like this.

03:06.120 --> 03:07.500
Really?

03:07.500 --> 03:09.250
Can we not talk about
my mother right now?

03:16.120 --> 03:18.710
[ Gasps ] Yes, I will
have some champagne.

03:18.710 --> 03:20.170
You should not
have any champagne.

03:20.170 --> 03:22.880
We are going
straight to the hospital.

03:22.880 --> 03:24.460
Uh, club soda?

03:24.460 --> 03:26.120
Same for me, please,
Katie. Thank you.
Coming right up.

03:30.580 --> 03:32.540
[ Birds chirping ]

03:35.290 --> 03:36.670
[ Brakes squeal ]

03:42.790 --> 03:44.080
[ Car doors close ]

03:45.290 --> 03:46.580
Dr. Corridan:
Welcome, welcome.

03:46.580 --> 03:47.500
Here are your charts.

03:47.500 --> 03:49.500
Dr. Avery.

03:49.500 --> 03:50.380
Dr. Grey.

03:50.380 --> 03:51.330
Kepner.

03:51.330 --> 03:52.830
Right. Sorry.

03:52.830 --> 03:54.420
I -- I know his name
because it's on

03:54.420 --> 03:55.880
all our stationery.
Right.

03:55.880 --> 03:57.420
A patient
and a donor --

03:57.420 --> 03:58.790
two of them
here together,

03:58.790 --> 04:01.830
same time, same day,
perfect match...

04:01.830 --> 04:03.920
[ Sighs ] It's like
winning the lottery.

04:03.920 --> 04:05.580
I mean, if you call
a brain-dead kid

04:05.580 --> 04:06.880
a lottery ticket,
then, yeah.

04:06.880 --> 04:08.040
Of course.

04:08.040 --> 04:10.080
And it's a horrible loss.
Uh, that was --

04:10.080 --> 04:11.540
I-I'm just thrilled
that you're both here

04:11.540 --> 04:13.250
to make this possible.

04:13.250 --> 04:15.920
The donor patient's room
is at the end of this ICU.

04:15.920 --> 04:17.330
And you have
the donor consent forms?

04:17.330 --> 04:19.580
Yeah, before we get to
that, uh, Mr. Young

04:19.580 --> 04:21.670
is going to need you
to explain to him

04:21.670 --> 04:24.000
why there's nothing more
you can do for his son.

04:24.000 --> 04:25.500
What? No one's
told him that yet?

04:25.500 --> 04:26.580
I thought he knew
we were coming.

04:26.580 --> 04:28.250
Well, he does.
It -- It's just that,

04:28.250 --> 04:30.120
he's had a bit of trouble
accepting what's happened,

04:30.120 --> 04:31.960
as I'm sure
you can understand.

04:31.960 --> 04:33.170
You told me
very clearly

04:33.170 --> 04:34.750
that the patient's father
was on board.

04:34.750 --> 04:35.920
Now, hold on.

04:35.920 --> 04:38.080
I never said that he agreed.
I merely said --

04:38.080 --> 04:40.040
So he thinks
that we're coming

04:40.040 --> 04:42.120
to save his kid,
not take his organs.

04:42.120 --> 04:44.620
I thought that,
once you had examined the boy,

04:44.620 --> 04:46.500
it'd be better
coming from you.

04:46.500 --> 04:48.790
Eric: I'm just glad
you're here.

04:48.790 --> 04:50.920
I mean, Dr. Corridan said that
there's nothing he could do.

04:50.920 --> 04:52.380
Then he said
there was another doctor

04:52.380 --> 04:53.330
who was coming in
from Seattle.

04:53.330 --> 04:54.750
I was like --

04:54.750 --> 04:56.620
I mean, it's great, right?
Th-There's hope.

04:56.620 --> 04:59.080
So, okay.
What's the plan?

04:59.080 --> 05:02.040
I mean, you -- you -- you want
to do some tests?

05:02.040 --> 05:03.040
Surgery?

05:03.040 --> 05:05.210
Obviously,
you want to examine him,

05:05.210 --> 05:07.960
but how long
before you think he'll wake up?

05:07.960 --> 05:10.620
Mr. Young, I'm af--
Eric, Eric, please.

05:10.620 --> 05:13.040
Eric --
It's his birthday.

05:13.040 --> 05:15.710
Did I tell you that?

05:15.710 --> 05:17.120
Double digits,
he kept saying.

05:17.120 --> 05:18.670
[ Chuckles ]

05:18.670 --> 05:20.710
I mean, he was having
the time of his life
up on that mountain.

05:20.710 --> 05:23.250
"Just one more run, Dad.

05:23.250 --> 05:25.500
Just one more run..."

05:25.500 --> 05:28.170
Eric, I'm afraid we have
some difficult news.

05:28.170 --> 05:30.790
We've looked at
Brian's scans,

05:30.790 --> 05:34.170
and, unfortunately,
Dr. Corridan was right.

05:34.170 --> 05:37.420
There's nothing that we can do
for your son.

05:37.420 --> 05:40.330
[ Scoffs ]

05:40.330 --> 05:42.170
Then why are you here?

05:42.170 --> 05:44.040
We are here...

05:44.040 --> 05:46.790
because we wanted to
talk to you about...

05:46.790 --> 05:49.000
donating
your son's organs.

05:49.000 --> 05:50.710
[ Scoffs ]

05:56.580 --> 05:59.250
No.

05:59.250 --> 06:02.250
You're here
to help my son.

06:02.250 --> 06:05.040
I understand
how difficult this is --
Difficult?

06:05.040 --> 06:07.000
If you understood what you were
asking, you wouldn't...

06:07.000 --> 06:08.500
Mr. Young --

06:08.500 --> 06:11.620
I know what we're asking.

06:11.620 --> 06:14.960
When all you want is to
have him back, to hold him.

06:14.960 --> 06:18.880
I know the thought of letting
any part of him go feels...

06:18.880 --> 06:20.790
impossible.

06:20.790 --> 06:23.420
You're the only that can make
this decision.

06:23.420 --> 06:24.920
We understand that.

06:24.920 --> 06:25.920
We wouldn't ask you
to do something

06:25.920 --> 06:27.330
that you're not
comfortable doing.

06:27.330 --> 06:29.000
And if ultimately
you don't want to do this,

06:29.000 --> 06:30.380
that's fine.

06:30.380 --> 06:34.290
We are here
to support you either way.

06:34.290 --> 06:37.170
All I know is...

06:37.170 --> 06:41.290
is when I lost my son...

06:41.290 --> 06:43.960
I just needed to find
a little meaning in it.

06:43.960 --> 06:46.460
♪♪

07:04.750 --> 07:06.670
Where do I sign?

07:30.960 --> 07:32.960
This way
to Caroline's room.

07:32.960 --> 07:35.080
Her parents are very eager
to meet you, Dr. Avery.

07:36.880 --> 07:39.460
This is Risa
and Mary Hodges.

07:39.460 --> 07:41.080
Well, it's a pleasure
to meet you both.

07:41.080 --> 07:43.420
Listen, we're grateful
that you're here,

07:43.420 --> 07:44.790
that you came all this way,

07:44.790 --> 07:47.210
but our daughter's
met dozens of doctors,

07:47.210 --> 07:48.500
each one ordering more tests,

07:48.500 --> 07:50.080
putting her through more hell,

07:50.080 --> 07:52.380
making promises they had
no business making.

07:52.380 --> 07:54.460
Mary, maybe
let the guy say hello.

07:54.460 --> 07:57.330
She needs
the tumor gone.

07:57.330 --> 07:59.250
But she needs
her vocal cords.

07:59.250 --> 08:00.540
She needs her voice.

08:00.540 --> 08:02.920
So if this throat transplant
isn't real --

08:02.920 --> 08:04.290
I mean, if it's just another rug
you're gonna pull out

08:04.290 --> 08:06.670
from under her, then --
You're scared.

08:06.670 --> 08:08.580
I totally understand.

08:08.580 --> 08:11.000
Let me, um --
Let me start over.

08:11.000 --> 08:12.830
It's my fault.
I'm Dr. Avery.

08:12.830 --> 08:15.120
I am a double board-certified
plastic surgeon

08:15.120 --> 08:16.330
and ENT specialist.

08:16.330 --> 08:19.290
I'm also a dad.

08:19.290 --> 08:20.750
Now, I've come
a long way

08:20.750 --> 08:22.960
because I know that
I can help your daughter.

08:22.960 --> 08:24.710
And I do not make promises
that I can't keep.

08:29.670 --> 08:31.210
Mary: I just --
I still don't know

08:31.210 --> 08:32.710
if this is
the right thing.

08:32.710 --> 08:34.250
The laryngectomy is still
the safest --

08:34.250 --> 08:35.620
No, Mary, we agreed.

08:35.620 --> 08:36.920
They are not taking
her vocal cords.

08:36.920 --> 08:39.290
What if you go in there,
Dr. Avery,

08:39.290 --> 08:41.170
and you cut open
her throat,

08:41.170 --> 08:43.330
and the transplant
doesn't work?

08:43.330 --> 08:45.380
In that place, we'd be
looking at a permanent trach.

08:45.380 --> 08:46.710
Permanent. See?

08:46.710 --> 08:48.040
And you want to
risk that?

08:48.040 --> 08:49.620
He wouldn't do it if he didn't
think that he could.

08:51.380 --> 08:53.710
Would you?
This procedure gives her
the best chance at survival --

08:53.710 --> 08:56.380
at getting her voice back,
her whole life back.

08:58.040 --> 08:59.580
Mary, come on.

09:05.750 --> 09:08.250
[ Sighs ]

09:08.250 --> 09:09.540
Okay.

09:16.380 --> 09:17.750
Why are you doing that?
Doing what?

09:17.750 --> 09:19.460
Telling those moms
you're a dad

09:19.460 --> 09:20.750
to charm your way
into the room,

09:20.750 --> 09:22.330
using Samuel to --
It's my life.

09:22.330 --> 09:24.250
It happened.

09:24.250 --> 09:26.790
Yeah, it's my life, too,
but I don't use it to --
To what?

09:26.790 --> 09:28.580
Help that dad
make his decision?

09:28.580 --> 09:30.750
Help those moms
find a little bit of comfort?

09:30.750 --> 09:33.380
April, if you don't like it,
that is your problem.

09:33.380 --> 09:35.460
I'm not the one that asked you
to come here in the first place.

09:37.250 --> 09:40.040
Look, we have tonight
to prep for the surgery.

09:40.040 --> 09:41.880
I have somewhere
that I need to be.

09:41.880 --> 09:43.080
I will find you later.

09:43.080 --> 09:44.620
What --
Where do you need to be?

09:44.620 --> 09:46.210
It's Montana.
I'll find you later.

09:47.460 --> 09:50.540
♪♪

09:52.210 --> 09:55.120
[ Indistinct conversations ]

09:55.120 --> 09:58.460
[ Breathes deeply ]

10:11.830 --> 10:15.710
[ Cellphone rings ]
April --

10:15.710 --> 10:17.920
I laid out all of
Caroline's charts.

10:17.920 --> 10:19.830
Chinese food
is on the way.

10:19.830 --> 10:22.670
I know things are not the
greatest between us right now,

10:22.670 --> 10:24.830
but if we're gonna do
the surgery --

10:24.830 --> 10:27.210
Yeah, no,
I need to prep alone.

10:27.210 --> 10:27.880
I'll talk to you
tomorrow.

10:27.880 --> 10:29.750
Um --

10:29.750 --> 10:30.580
[ Scoffs ]

10:34.330 --> 10:36.670
[ Sighs ] Okay.

10:36.670 --> 10:38.000
[ Door bell jingles ]

10:40.330 --> 10:42.960
Carl, I thought
your doctor said

10:42.960 --> 10:45.250
to cut down
on the red meat.

10:45.250 --> 10:47.920
Carl: That's why
I'm sharing.

10:47.920 --> 10:50.210
You good?

10:50.210 --> 10:51.540
On the house
for new customers.

10:56.000 --> 10:57.500
Well, enjoy that.

11:04.540 --> 11:06.330
[ Cellphone rings ]

11:06.330 --> 11:08.000
Hello?

11:08.000 --> 11:11.540
No, this is
Dr. Kepner.

11:11.540 --> 11:12.880
No, I don't --
I don't know.

11:12.880 --> 11:15.580
Have you tried his room?

11:15.580 --> 11:16.960
I'm sorry. What?!

11:18.460 --> 11:20.790
April: There was a lesion
on the donor's throat,

11:20.790 --> 11:23.670
which means the transplant
is no longer an option.

11:23.670 --> 11:25.040
I am so sorry --

11:25.040 --> 11:26.290
Don't tell us you're sorry.

11:26.290 --> 11:28.120
You talked me into this.

11:28.120 --> 11:30.500
You said this was
the solution!

11:30.500 --> 11:32.580
And now, I mean,
if there's no donor,

11:32.580 --> 11:34.210
how do you fix
our daughter?!

11:34.210 --> 11:35.460
Mary, please,
stop yelling.

11:35.460 --> 11:37.830
If there's a time to yell,
Risa, this is it.

11:37.830 --> 11:39.830
The best way
to help your daughter

11:39.830 --> 11:42.250
is to do the laryngectomy,
which means --

11:42.250 --> 11:43.710
No, we know
what that means.

11:43.710 --> 11:47.710
That is removing her vocal cords
and her ability to speak.

11:47.710 --> 11:50.290
And we told Dr. Avery
it's not an option.

11:50.290 --> 11:54.500
At this point, I really think
it is her best chance.

11:54.500 --> 11:57.330
[ Sniffles ] And --
And what about Dr. Avery?

11:57.330 --> 11:59.170
Is that what
he thinks, too?

12:01.670 --> 12:05.830
I don't know where you are or
what you're doing, but call me!

12:05.830 --> 12:08.170
[ Sighs ] Damn it!

12:08.170 --> 12:09.250
[ Door bell jingles ]

12:11.750 --> 12:13.380
Oh, my --
Where have you been?

12:13.380 --> 12:16.380
I have been looking
everywhere for you.

12:16.380 --> 12:18.170
Corridan's called
a dozen times.

12:18.170 --> 12:19.580
I have been calling,
texting --

12:19.580 --> 12:21.750
Calm down.
You sent one text.

12:21.750 --> 12:23.500
[ Scoffs ]
No organs,
no surgery, right?

12:23.500 --> 12:25.290
Didn't hear anything else
after that,

12:25.290 --> 12:26.330
so I figured
I'd have a drink.

12:28.460 --> 12:31.170
Oh.
Battery died.

12:31.170 --> 12:33.620
Well, that's not very helpful,
now, is it?

12:33.620 --> 12:35.080
You're drunk.
You're pissed.

12:35.080 --> 12:37.120
Yeah, yeah,
uh-huh, I am.

12:37.120 --> 12:39.460
We lost the donor,
Caroline's repeat scans

12:39.460 --> 12:41.880
show more extensive
esophageal invasion,

12:41.880 --> 12:43.790
her parents are
a wreck, and --

12:43.790 --> 12:46.000
and you're -- you're here
getting drunk?

12:46.000 --> 12:48.960
Jackson.

12:48.960 --> 12:52.830
I got off work,
and I had a beer, April.

12:52.830 --> 12:55.540
Four beers, actually, and,
uh, some whiskey on top of that.

12:55.540 --> 12:57.120
What is wrong with you?

12:57.120 --> 12:58.380
Nothing.

12:58.380 --> 12:59.540
Nothing wrong with me.

12:59.540 --> 13:01.460
We have a patient
who's counting on us.

13:01.460 --> 13:03.540
No, not us. Me.

13:03.540 --> 13:05.380
And there's no organs,
there's nothing I can do,

13:05.380 --> 13:06.710
so just leave me
the hell alone.

13:06.710 --> 13:08.580
[ Scoffs ]

13:08.580 --> 13:09.920
I mean,
this isn't you.

13:09.920 --> 13:12.540
You don't get wasted in bars
and bail on your patients --

13:12.540 --> 13:14.040
I didn't bail on anyone!

13:14.040 --> 13:15.540
So, how we doing over here?

13:18.380 --> 13:19.420
Dessert?

13:19.420 --> 13:21.500
April: No, he's going home --
to sober up.

13:21.500 --> 13:23.120
He has work, right?

13:23.120 --> 13:24.540
In that case,
let me call you a cab.

13:24.540 --> 13:27.500
I'm walking.

13:27.500 --> 13:30.420
[ Door bell jingles,
door closes ]

13:33.120 --> 13:35.710
Can I get you something?

13:35.710 --> 13:37.120
No, I'm good.

13:39.000 --> 13:40.380
He left his book.

13:40.380 --> 13:43.620
"Techniques
in Oropharyngeal Surgery."

13:43.620 --> 13:44.670
Hmm.

13:44.670 --> 13:47.040
Airway reconstruction?

13:47.040 --> 13:49.580
Uh, throat...transplant.

13:49.580 --> 13:50.750
Supposed to be
a throat transplant.

13:50.750 --> 13:51.880
It just got scrapped.

13:51.880 --> 13:54.380
Total laryngectomy
not an option, huh?

13:54.380 --> 13:55.080
[ Chuckles ]

13:55.080 --> 13:56.420
I was a surgeon.

13:56.420 --> 13:58.250
That was many lifetimes ago.

13:58.250 --> 14:00.250
Really?

14:00.250 --> 14:02.750
You gave that up
for this?

14:02.750 --> 14:05.000
Well, this is not
all that different.

14:05.000 --> 14:07.500
People come to you in need,
you provide them comfort.

14:07.500 --> 14:10.540
They leave here feeling better
than when they came.

14:10.540 --> 14:12.710
And the hours are better,
and nobody dies.

14:12.710 --> 14:16.290
That I know of.
[ Chuckles ]

14:16.290 --> 14:17.540
Welcome to Bozeman,
Doctor...

14:17.540 --> 14:19.170
Uh, Kepner.
April Kepner.

14:19.170 --> 14:20.540
Robert Avery.

14:22.000 --> 14:23.920
Avery.
I'm -- I'm sorry.

14:23.920 --> 14:25.000
Like the hospital?

14:25.000 --> 14:27.670
Kinda.
Once upon a time.

14:27.670 --> 14:30.420
Let me know if you need
anything, okay?

14:30.420 --> 14:31.380
I -- I will.

14:41.500 --> 14:43.830
[ Knock on door ]

14:50.210 --> 14:52.040
[ Knock on door ]

14:56.620 --> 14:58.500
We still need to find a way
to help Caroline.

14:58.500 --> 14:59.670
Oh.
What time is it?

14:59.670 --> 15:00.330
It's early.

15:03.460 --> 15:05.080
What?
Are you okay?

15:05.080 --> 15:07.500
Yeah, I'm fine.

15:07.500 --> 15:09.500
Hurry up and get dressed.
We should get to work.

15:09.500 --> 15:10.210
Sure.

15:11.670 --> 15:13.040
I hate this.

15:13.040 --> 15:15.000
I don't see how
we could do anything

15:15.000 --> 15:17.500
but the laryngectomy,
but I hate the laryngectomy.

15:17.500 --> 15:19.250
Seems like she'd
have had a better shot

15:19.250 --> 15:20.500
if you'd taken her
to Grey Sloan.

15:20.500 --> 15:22.170
She's not stable enough
to move. You know that.

15:22.170 --> 15:23.170
No, not now.

15:23.170 --> 15:24.750
I'm just saying,
I don't know why

15:24.750 --> 15:26.620
we had to come
all the way out here.

15:26.620 --> 15:29.170
Do you?

15:29.170 --> 15:31.080
The last time
I worked on a kid

15:31.080 --> 15:33.380
with a throat tumor,
we did a staged procedure.

15:33.380 --> 15:35.670
I did a radical excision
and a trach first,

15:35.670 --> 15:37.170
and then we did
a skin flap.

15:37.170 --> 15:38.710
She doesn't have
that kind of time.

15:38.710 --> 15:40.040
Yeah, I -- I know.
I'm just --

15:40.040 --> 15:41.790
But if we'd gotten
to this last night --

15:41.790 --> 15:44.210
Then we still would not have had
enough time for the flap.

15:44.210 --> 15:45.710
I mean, come on.
You made your point.

15:45.710 --> 15:47.830
I was drunk, April.
I get it.

15:47.830 --> 15:49.540
I don't need you to
monitor everything --
I'm not!

15:49.540 --> 15:51.710
I am just trying to come up
with a fix for our patient,

15:51.710 --> 15:53.960
regardless of the fact that
you don't even want me here.

15:53.960 --> 15:55.750
And yet
you're still here.

15:55.750 --> 15:57.250
'Cause you and my mother
are such good friends

15:57.250 --> 15:58.670
that she chose you instead of
asking me who I want.

15:58.670 --> 16:00.250
Oh, my God!

16:00.250 --> 16:03.120
I was friends with her long
before you and I were eve--

16:03.120 --> 16:04.290
I respect her!

16:04.290 --> 16:06.210
I respect
what she's built...
Great!

16:06.210 --> 16:08.250
...and what the means --
Good for you!

16:08.250 --> 16:10.540
You know, your mom says the
difference between the two of us

16:10.540 --> 16:12.790
is that you were born with money
and I had to earn it.

16:12.790 --> 16:14.580
It's why she and I
are more alike.

16:14.580 --> 16:16.960
You think this is a contest
between you and me?

16:16.960 --> 16:18.250
Who's the most alike?
Who's the most appreciative?

16:18.250 --> 16:19.750
No, Jackson!
[ Cellphone vibrating ]

16:19.750 --> 16:22.290
That is not the point
of any of this --
Shut up.

16:22.290 --> 16:24.080
What? Don't tell me
to shut up.

16:24.080 --> 16:25.210
Are you kidding me --
Shut up.

16:25.210 --> 16:26.830
[ Vibrating continues ]

16:28.750 --> 16:30.290
If her airway's
collapsed, we'll have
to crike her right away.

16:30.290 --> 16:31.420
Take her
straight to the O.R.

16:31.420 --> 16:32.750
Dr. Corridan,
what are we looking at?

16:32.750 --> 16:34.330
Jackson:
The nurses paged us, 911.

16:34.330 --> 16:35.460
What is happening here?

16:35.460 --> 16:36.880
[ Quietly ]
Caroline is being discharged.

16:36.880 --> 16:38.960
What?! No, she's not
stable enough to move.

16:38.960 --> 16:40.830
The doctors at Baylor
think she is.

16:40.830 --> 16:42.670
What doctors at Baylor?

16:42.670 --> 16:44.080
The one we called.

16:44.080 --> 16:45.580
I spoke
with Dr. Rapkin there.

16:45.580 --> 16:47.920
She has a new method she
believes will help Caroline.

16:47.920 --> 16:49.750
Mary: Aggressive chemo-radiation
with staged excision

16:49.750 --> 16:50.750
after two weeks.

16:50.750 --> 16:52.080
Yes, we have already
rejected that --

16:52.080 --> 16:55.000
We've gone through every
possible alternative.

16:55.000 --> 16:58.290
Risa, there comes a point
when you just have to hear --

16:58.290 --> 17:01.460
You think I don't hear you?!

17:01.460 --> 17:02.790
All of you?

17:02.790 --> 17:04.880
My daughter has no voice.

17:04.880 --> 17:08.040
We are her voice.

17:08.040 --> 17:09.670
We are not
gonna let her down

17:09.670 --> 17:11.830
just because we stopped
asking questions.

17:13.620 --> 17:16.250
We asked, you said no.

17:16.250 --> 17:18.620
We're leaving.

17:18.620 --> 17:21.380
They have the right to move her
if they feel it's necessary.

17:21.380 --> 17:23.330
No. It is too dangerous
to move her anywhere.

17:23.330 --> 17:25.000
That girl could choke
on her own tumor, okay?

17:25.000 --> 17:27.040
If you move her,
she could die -- period.

17:27.040 --> 17:28.580
Dr. Corridan: Okay.
So, y-y-you --

17:28.580 --> 17:29.960
you'll need to fill out
an AMA form.

17:29.960 --> 17:33.000
Legal reasons.

17:33.000 --> 17:34.750
Tell us what you have.

17:34.750 --> 17:36.210
Tell us why we should stay.

17:39.040 --> 17:43.620
[ Sighs ] We've been down
every road -- every one.

17:43.620 --> 17:45.250
There are no other options.

17:45.250 --> 17:47.750
We do the laryngectomy,
Caroline lives.

17:47.750 --> 17:48.790
It's that simple.

17:52.120 --> 17:53.540
[ Mary sighs ]

18:00.380 --> 18:03.000
Risa:
We're going to Baylor.

18:03.000 --> 18:05.580
It's what she wants --
what we all want.

18:14.000 --> 18:16.710
We'll fix it.
We will fix her voice.

18:18.000 --> 18:19.920
Listen, what Dr. Avery means
is that --

18:19.920 --> 18:21.380
I have an idea
is what I mean.

18:21.380 --> 18:23.920
I told you that I don't
break my promises, right?

18:23.920 --> 18:25.670
I promise you this.

18:25.670 --> 18:27.540
I have an idea that
I think is gonna work.

18:27.540 --> 18:29.210
All right,
I'll call Dr. Rapkin.

18:29.210 --> 18:30.210
I will.

18:30.210 --> 18:32.540
I'll call everybody
that I can.

18:32.540 --> 18:34.670
This is gonna work,
okay?

18:34.670 --> 18:37.080
Give Dr. Kepner and I
a little bit of time

18:37.080 --> 18:39.380
and do not move her.

18:39.380 --> 18:40.210
Please.

18:47.040 --> 18:48.830
We get on a plane
tomorrow at 3:00.

18:50.330 --> 18:51.960
You've got till then.

18:56.540 --> 18:59.460
Okay.
So what's your idea?

18:59.460 --> 19:01.670
I don't have one.

19:01.670 --> 19:02.580
What? You just --

19:02.580 --> 19:04.000
Yes, I lied,
but they can't move her,

19:04.000 --> 19:05.710
and I just needed
a little more time.

19:05.710 --> 19:07.120
What is the matter
with you?

19:07.120 --> 19:09.250
Why are you
torturing this poor girl?

19:09.250 --> 19:12.000
You just made a promise
that you know you can't keep,

19:12.000 --> 19:13.750
that you know
we can't deliver.

19:13.750 --> 19:15.040
We can find
a way to deliver.

19:15.040 --> 19:17.420
Where? Where --
Wh-Where are we gonna find it?

19:17.420 --> 19:19.790
At the diner?!

19:19.790 --> 19:21.500
What?

19:21.500 --> 19:24.540
When are you gonna tell me
that you found your father?

19:24.540 --> 19:27.580
Your father, Jackson --
your long-lost, deadbeat dad?

19:27.580 --> 19:29.960
The distinguished-hippie-
former-surgeon Dr. Avery,

19:29.960 --> 19:31.960
who slings hash
at the local diner?

19:31.960 --> 19:33.290
He's the whole reason
we're here!

19:35.250 --> 19:36.790
No, I came here
to help a patient.

19:36.790 --> 19:39.250
Don't lie to me.

19:39.250 --> 19:43.420
And worse yet, don't lie
to Caroline and her parents.

19:43.420 --> 19:45.500
We are only here
'cause of your freakin' father,

19:45.500 --> 19:46.710
and now that kid
is gonna die.

20:02.880 --> 20:03.670
Night-night, baby.
Sleep well.

20:03.670 --> 20:04.540
Be good for Grandma, okay?
Love you.

20:04.540 --> 20:05.750
Love you, nugget.

20:05.750 --> 20:08.210
Mwah!
[ Both chuckle ]

20:08.210 --> 20:09.210
[ Cellphone clicks ]

20:19.790 --> 20:21.420
Why didn't you
just tell me?

20:27.290 --> 20:29.290
All right. [ Scoffs ]

20:29.290 --> 20:30.420
Forget it.

20:34.290 --> 20:37.210
"You good?"

20:37.210 --> 20:41.120
What?

20:41.120 --> 20:42.460
I sat there, staring at him
across the room.

20:42.460 --> 20:46.080
Figured, you know,
eventually, he'll see me,

20:46.080 --> 20:50.670
recognize...something --
my face, my eyes,

20:50.670 --> 20:52.830
just...anything.

20:52.830 --> 20:57.290
And that's I got was,
"You good?"

21:00.420 --> 21:02.460
Like, literally,
that's it.

21:02.460 --> 21:06.330
No recognition, nothing.

21:06.330 --> 21:10.210
Like I was...

21:10.210 --> 21:12.540
anyone.

21:12.540 --> 21:14.710
No one.

21:14.710 --> 21:16.380
So talk to him.

21:16.380 --> 21:17.420
Yeah, I tried.

21:17.420 --> 21:20.420
I -- I wanted to.

21:20.420 --> 21:25.750
I went, and I sat there,
waited...

21:25.750 --> 21:29.080
[ Sighs deeply ]

21:29.080 --> 21:32.750
I got a million things
to say to that guy.

21:32.750 --> 21:34.460
Thinking about it
my whole...

21:39.210 --> 21:40.710
Tell him
what an ass he was

21:40.710 --> 21:43.790
for walking out
on his family, his kid...

21:47.210 --> 21:49.380
He couldn't hack it
as an Avery. Join the club.

21:53.040 --> 21:55.120
Could still show up.

21:55.120 --> 21:58.290
Pick something --
uh, birthday, graduation.

21:58.290 --> 21:59.710
Show the hell up.

22:05.830 --> 22:08.790
That's what I was gonna say --
all that.

22:08.790 --> 22:10.170
Then, uh...

22:15.210 --> 22:18.000
Then he...

22:18.000 --> 22:21.620
He looked me
right in the eye.

22:21.620 --> 22:25.250
[ Chuckles ]

22:25.250 --> 22:26.750
He doesn't know
his own son.

22:30.540 --> 22:32.380
So make him know you.

22:47.920 --> 22:50.380
This is stupid.
No, it's not.

22:55.790 --> 22:57.710
All right, well, you can go.
I'm not going.

22:59.960 --> 23:01.040
We're not married.

23:01.040 --> 23:02.290
It's not like
who I talk to

23:02.290 --> 23:03.830
or don't talk to
is any of your business anyway.

23:03.830 --> 23:05.460
Yeah,
it is my business,

23:05.460 --> 23:07.960
because we have a job to do,
and you're not here.

23:07.960 --> 23:09.170
And you're not
gonna be here

23:09.170 --> 23:10.330
till you say
what you need to say.

23:10.330 --> 23:11.960
So go say it.

23:11.960 --> 23:14.880
Then it will be over...

23:14.880 --> 23:16.250
and we can get back to work.
[ Inhales deeply ]

23:20.460 --> 23:21.580
[ Sighs ]

23:36.710 --> 23:39.290
[ Door bell jingles ]
[ Clears throat ]

23:39.290 --> 23:40.500
Hey, back again.

23:40.500 --> 23:42.580
Sorry, we're closed.

23:48.080 --> 23:50.000
I've got some meatloaf
left over in the back.

23:50.000 --> 23:51.420
I could fix up something to go
if you'd like --

23:51.420 --> 23:52.580
[ Door bell jingles ]
I'm Jackson Avery.

23:55.880 --> 23:56.670
I'm your son.

24:00.250 --> 24:01.710
[ Door bell jingles ]

24:03.920 --> 24:05.040
Oh, my God.

24:10.080 --> 24:11.500
[ Chuckling ]
Oh, my God.

24:15.120 --> 24:18.880
Jackson.
Oh, son.

24:18.880 --> 24:20.040
Oh, Jackson!

24:20.040 --> 24:21.790
[ Laughing ]

24:21.790 --> 24:24.710
Oh, good God!

24:24.710 --> 24:25.620
Oh, my God.

24:25.620 --> 24:28.040
Come inside.
Oh, Jackson.

24:28.040 --> 24:31.460
I'm sorry, it's just, my brain
is going a little...you know?

24:31.460 --> 24:33.380
Robert:
You want to sit?

24:33.380 --> 24:35.290
Of course not.
You've been sitting.

24:35.290 --> 24:37.040
Why didn't you just --

24:37.040 --> 24:39.670
I mean, I don't blame you,
but...

24:39.670 --> 24:44.250
I'm sorry, I do not know
what to say here.

24:44.250 --> 24:46.920
Are you here for work, too,
at the hospital?

24:46.920 --> 24:49.290
You and your friend,
uh, April, was it?

24:49.290 --> 24:51.170
The surgeon?

24:51.170 --> 24:52.580
Yeah.

24:52.580 --> 24:56.620
You're a surgeon.

24:56.620 --> 24:57.540
I am, yeah.

24:57.540 --> 24:59.580
Uh, Plastics and ENT.

24:59.580 --> 25:01.040
Of course.
Of course you are.

25:01.040 --> 25:03.540
[ Knocks on bar ]
Good God.

25:03.540 --> 25:06.080
And your mom?
Is she here, too?

25:08.250 --> 25:09.670
This your place?

25:09.670 --> 25:12.580
It gives me
a roof over my head

25:12.580 --> 25:13.960
and weekends off
to play golf,

25:13.960 --> 25:14.960
food on the table.

25:14.960 --> 25:16.880
Speaking of which...

25:16.880 --> 25:18.920
Oh, wait right there.

25:18.920 --> 25:22.420
[ Clears throat ]

25:22.420 --> 25:24.120
My own blend.

25:24.120 --> 25:25.830
I've been working
with these local guys --

25:25.830 --> 25:27.000
Great guys.
You'd like them.

25:28.710 --> 25:30.960
I don't know why
I just said that.

25:30.960 --> 25:33.210
I have no idea
who you'd like.

25:33.210 --> 25:35.170
Anyway, we're thinking
of opening up a little
business on the side.

25:35.170 --> 25:36.830
Nothing big, you know?

25:36.830 --> 25:39.000
Just putting it out there
for the tourists and such.

25:50.380 --> 25:51.210
[ Sighs ]
You're right.

25:51.210 --> 25:52.880
Incredible, huh?

25:52.880 --> 25:54.500
Chicory.

25:54.500 --> 25:55.790
[ Chuckles softly ]

25:55.790 --> 25:57.500
Listen to me,

25:57.500 --> 26:00.500
yapping away
like some kind of idiot.

26:00.500 --> 26:02.290
Tell me something.

26:02.290 --> 26:04.120
Anything, everything.

26:04.120 --> 26:05.790
I know nothing.

26:09.750 --> 26:11.080
Here.

26:11.080 --> 26:12.380
Here we go.

26:21.500 --> 26:22.920
God, it's good
to see you.

26:22.920 --> 26:25.000
Look at you.

26:25.000 --> 26:28.330
[ Both sigh ]

26:29.210 --> 26:31.880
I'm Head of Plastics and board
chair at Grey Sloan Memorial.

26:31.880 --> 26:35.880
I'm, uh, developing a new
protocol with skin grafts,

26:35.880 --> 26:38.540
particularly burn victims,
and --

26:38.540 --> 26:42.670
No, I'm not talking, um...

26:42.670 --> 26:44.330
Of course you're amazing.

26:44.330 --> 26:46.960
You know, with your mom's help,
your name --

26:46.960 --> 26:48.170
I'm sure you're successful.

26:48.170 --> 26:50.880
No, what I mean is,
uh...

26:50.880 --> 26:53.960
What you do,
your family.

26:53.960 --> 26:55.710
Are you married?

26:55.710 --> 26:57.250
Kids?

26:57.250 --> 27:00.620
I guess what I'm asking is,
are you happy?

27:04.540 --> 27:05.420
Yeah, of course.

27:05.420 --> 27:07.000
No.

27:07.000 --> 27:08.460
Not "of course."

27:11.670 --> 27:14.420
I'm happy.

27:14.420 --> 27:16.960
Are you?

27:16.960 --> 27:18.620
Honestly, yeah.
Yeah, I am.

27:22.500 --> 27:25.540
But for me,
the whole Avery thing...

27:28.000 --> 27:30.170
I just couldn't do it.

27:30.170 --> 27:32.920
If it works
for you, great.

27:32.920 --> 27:35.380
For me...

27:36.750 --> 27:39.670
The galas, the hand-shaking --
it wasn't my thing.

27:42.620 --> 27:45.210
Your thing.

27:45.210 --> 27:47.460
But when I found out
what was,

27:47.460 --> 27:50.460
you couldn't
drag me away, pal.

27:52.500 --> 27:54.580
From your diner
in Montana?

27:54.580 --> 27:58.040
The night
that I met your mother,

27:58.040 --> 28:02.420
it was an annual
Avery Gala.

28:02.420 --> 28:04.580
I was stuffed
in a thousand-dollar tux.

28:04.580 --> 28:08.830
She...was the most beautiful
woman in the room,

28:08.830 --> 28:11.000
going toe-to-toe
with some rich dinosaur

28:11.000 --> 28:13.000
about God-knows-what.

28:13.000 --> 28:15.380
And she had a laugh...
Oh.

28:18.290 --> 28:21.830
I introduced myself,
and she ignored me

28:21.830 --> 28:24.960
half the night
just to spite me.

28:24.960 --> 28:28.330
I was born into that life,
but she was born for it.

28:33.000 --> 28:36.040
So you took off.

28:36.040 --> 28:38.540
You know your mother.

28:38.540 --> 28:41.710
Her expectations are...
crushing.

28:44.540 --> 28:46.880
How about you don't
talk about her anymore?

28:46.880 --> 28:48.620
I'm sorry.
You're right.

28:48.620 --> 28:50.830
She is your mother --
That's true --
she is my mother.

28:54.540 --> 28:55.880
And I don't know you.

28:55.880 --> 28:57.330
Jackson --

28:57.330 --> 28:58.330
Forget it.

28:58.330 --> 29:01.080
Listen...

29:01.080 --> 29:02.710
[ Door bell jingles ]

29:08.380 --> 29:10.040
How'd it go?
Don't.

29:10.040 --> 29:11.830
Jackson --
Just don't ask.

29:31.250 --> 29:34.000
[ Sighs ] We got to
come up with something

29:34.000 --> 29:35.960
to save
this girl's voice.

29:35.960 --> 29:37.670
There's got to be
something, right?

29:41.830 --> 29:44.290
You want to talk about it,
what happened with your dad?

29:45.880 --> 29:47.580
You know what? Maybe we could do
a staged procedure.

29:47.580 --> 29:48.960
I could excise
the tumor now,

29:48.960 --> 29:50.540
and we could wait
on a transplant donor.

29:50.540 --> 29:52.460
No, it wouldn't work.

29:52.460 --> 29:54.420
She'd need
another course of radiation,

29:54.420 --> 29:56.210
which would make her
a bad surgical candidate.

29:56.210 --> 29:58.960
Yeah.

29:58.960 --> 30:01.420
Yeah, we talked.

30:01.420 --> 30:04.080
He talked, really --
a lot.

30:04.080 --> 30:06.670
About how hard it was
being an Avery

30:06.670 --> 30:08.290
and...surgery and --

30:08.290 --> 30:10.380
[ Snaps fingers ]
Temporary stent.

30:10.380 --> 30:11.500
Erosion and bleeding,
right?

30:11.500 --> 30:14.380
Crap.

30:14.380 --> 30:18.000
He was just so damn polite,
and...

30:18.000 --> 30:19.830
What about, um,
the animal studies?

30:19.830 --> 30:21.620
Okay.

30:21.620 --> 30:23.120
Uh...

30:23.120 --> 30:24.750
I just kind of
clammed up.

30:24.750 --> 30:25.750
I didn't say anything.

30:25.750 --> 30:28.210
Really, he was...

30:28.210 --> 30:30.710
just like...warm?
I don't know...

30:30.710 --> 30:32.040
He was -- happy!

30:36.290 --> 30:39.880
I definitely didn't picture him,
like, happy without me.

30:39.880 --> 30:43.500
He talked a lot,
didn't say anything about me.

30:45.170 --> 30:48.000
Nothing.

30:48.000 --> 30:53.040
Talked about Mom's laugh,
his stupid tuxedo, coffee.

30:53.040 --> 30:55.620
I felt really stupid.

30:55.620 --> 30:57.250
You're not.

30:57.250 --> 30:59.210
Never occurred to me, all that
time, that he didn't even...

31:03.790 --> 31:06.120
He really didn't even
miss me.

31:06.120 --> 31:09.540
You don't know that.
Oh, I do now.

31:09.540 --> 31:10.830
I really do.

31:10.830 --> 31:13.500
It didn't even occur to the guy
to pretend otherwise.

31:16.710 --> 31:17.880
How do you
go up to somebody

31:17.880 --> 31:19.420
and tell them
what an ass they've been

31:19.420 --> 31:20.540
when they're just
smiling at you,

31:20.540 --> 31:23.000
